[BEGIN] THIS much Nina Funnell knows about the man who held a box-cutter blade to her throat on an autumn's evening in May 2007.

She knows he had an olive complexion. She knows he had bushy eyebrows and a five o’clock shadow. She knows – although she cringes at the stereotype it encourages – that he spoke with a thick, Middle Eastern accent. He attacked from behind, she remembers that, and dragged her into a park opposite a girls’ high school in an affluent Sydney suburb.
